    "summaries": {
        "README.md": "The provided file is a detailed documentation of a Deep Packet Inspection (DPI) engine, a system used to examine the contents of network packets. The DPI engine is designed to identify and control application usage based on the traffic flowing through the network.\n\nHere is a summary of the key points:\n\n### Overview\n\n* The DPI engine is a C++ project that reads network captures, extracts protocol fields, and applies blocking rules.\n* The engine uses a multi-threaded architecture for high performance.\n\n### Components\n\n* `pcap_reader`: reads network captures from files.\n* `packet_parser`: extracts protocol fields from raw bytes.\n* `sni_extractor`: extracts domain names from TLS and HTTP traffic.\n* `types`: defines data structures used throughout the project.\n* `dpi_engine`: the main orchestrator that ties everything together.\n\n### Workflow\n\n1. Read network capture from file.\n2. Parse each packet to extract protocol fields.\n3. Create a Five-Tuple (source IP, destination IP, source port, destination port, protocol) to identify the flow.\n4. Extract SNI (Server Name Indication) from TLS traffic.\n5. Apply blocking rules based on the extracted SNI, app type, and source IP.\n6. Forward or drop packets based on the blocking rules.\n\n### Blocking Rules\n\n* The DPI engine supports three types of blocking rules: IP, app, and domain.\n* Rules can be configured using command-line arguments.\n\n### Multi-threaded Architecture\n\n* The DPI engine uses a producer-consumer pattern with thread-safe queues.\n* The engine creates multiple load balancer threads that distribute work across fast path threads.\n* Each fast path thread processes packets and applies blocking rules.\n\n### Extending the Project\n\n* The documentation provides ideas for improvement, including adding more app signatures, bandwidth throttling, live statistics dashboard, QUIC/HTTP3 support, and persistent rules.\n\nOverall, the DPI engine is a comprehensive system that demonstrates network protocol parsing, deep packet inspection, flow tracking, and multi-threaded architecture."
    },
